I'm a ranger, and in all honesty I could really care less if a scale or book dropped off one of the dragons.  Lets pretend I'm a bard or paladin and I look to see that by chance I can finally make the dragon raid this week, maybe twice a month I can usually make it because I might not be able to do a raid at 1:00 in the morning.  I look at the raid this week and see that paladin or bard that is leading it, barely knows anything about what he or she is doing (Let's face it, you don't really have to know a whole lot to take down Naggy).  The bard or paladin has been on maybe one raid and knows very little about the zone or how to organize groups.  7 hours later, the dragon drops my book or scale and it goes to the inept leader of the raid.  I can see how it could be frustrating for some people and can't really with a straight face give them the &quot;too bad, so sad&quot; speech because I repeat to them &quot;if you don't like the rules, don't go on the raid&quot;.  And in response to the &quot;don't go on pickup raids then&quot; idea, it's rather difficult to do that when entire guilds don't stop levelling so that all of it's bards and paladins can get their epics and excuse me if I'm not in one of the super dooper guilds that can do this.<br>
<br>
In conclusion, yes the &quot;if you don't like the rules, don't go on the raid&quot; speech that we've all heard a hundred times does apply here.  But I can't help to sympathize with those paladins and bards that have 20 AA points because they're trying to hold back on levelling until they get their epic piece only to learn that the raid that they can finally attend some inept raid leader is calling that item for himself or herself. <p>Yalladar Valleycrest<BR>
